<title>Pooled variances</title>
<p id="_556d8392-c259-c870-22c7-c99d4ff9557e">Experimenters in general are weIl advised to subdivide lengthy measurements into a number of shorter ones, whenever feasible. This gives them the possibility — should anything have gone wrong — at least to be aware of the problem and to know roughly when it occurred. If the results do not indicate an anomaly, the partial results must be combined in such a way that the outcome characterizes the entire measuring period.</p>

<p id="_439df5a3-ba0b-ed42-ef9c-5c0c6b93010c">Problems with recent measurements have led us to re-consider the question of how experimental values for the variance, obtained in sequences of runs, should be used to arrive at a “best” overall estimate.</p>

<p id="_ceeb216e-2cc1-a0cf-dd8e-1b86e9828a34">This problem occurs rather frequently and, no doubt, has been treated many times. A few years ago we looked at the special case of two samples <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/>. In what follows these earlier findings are generalized to include an arbitrary number m of samples. It is shown that the contributions arising from the differences between the individual mean values can be incorporated in those terms that involve only the measured variances.</p>

<p id="_7ec4cf48-1975-9d9b-f34e-f175a314afe6">Suppose that we have to deal with a situation which is “under statistical control”. What we actually require is that the first two moments of the number <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>x</mi></math></stem> of events, counted in a given time interval, show no significant trend with time.</p>

<p id="_c4b143c0-6273-c95e-6496-315e4ba6392f">Now consider measurements that have been performed on <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>m</mi></math></stem> samples, of size <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mtext> </mtext><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></stem>, taken randomly from sorne stable population. Let the results be available in the form of me an values <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> and variances <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msubsup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></math></stem> (for a single measurement), which have been obtained by forming from the measurements <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></mrow></msub></math></stem> the quantities</p>

<formula id="eq1"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></munderover><msub><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></mrow></msub></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_38d1fec4-9318-42e1-6aa1-00aa2d262d4c">and</p>

<formula id="eq2"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msubsup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></mfrac><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>.</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_57d78463-2635-6b69-2c79-6dd565d5f5a7">This allows us to form the weighted mean value</p>

<formula id="_f553b665-35a6-576f-b822-90b60f90684b" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mover accent="true"><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle></mrow></mfrac><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></munderover><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_901246e3-d04a-6f5b-c732-3f81770ad00c">where</p>

<formula id="_8b6b9795-c0de-d61e-ac21-8a974b027515" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle><mo>=</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></munderover><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_4967e4e8-245b-c8b9-7c50-c8c16d2c5c0c">is the total number of measurements performed. Note that all the variances <xref target="eq2"/> refer to a single measurement <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></mrow></msub></math></stem>, not to a mean value <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem>.</p>

<p id="_bd732ed0-0e15-2346-14f8-73d0eba25cf4">Our problem is to evaluate, on the basis of the data given in <xref target="eq1"/> and <xref target="eq2"/>, a value for the variance of a single measurement, denoted by <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></stem>. According to the definition of a variance, we have, considering all the <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle></math></stem> measurements performed, the estimation</p>

<formula id="eq3"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></mfrac><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></munderover><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mover accent="true"><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>.</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_7900d24c-ef3f-6fe3-a6d4-d9ab417b4bc1">This expression will now be rearranged. In a first step we easily find</p>

<formula id="_b6cba292-4200-9a39-a26e-d799c3319e7d" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>⋅</mo><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></munderover><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mfenced open="[" close="]"><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mover accent="true"><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></stem></formula>

<formula id="eq4"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><munder><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></munder><munder><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></munder><mfenced open="[" close="]"><mrow><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mover accent="true"><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mover accent="true"><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced><mo>.</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_323020d4-c92b-44aa-792f-8e58db550b62">Since according to <xref target="eq1"/></p>

<formula id="_796bae4c-5bff-2e96-d82c-811058e28536" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_60308510-6f2b-0f18-8a64-5e884370d9a3">we arrive, by using <xref target="eq2"/>, at the form</p>

<formula id="eq5"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></mfrac><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mfenced open="[" close="]"><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><msubsup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mover accent="true"><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>.</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_5833d43f-ce4e-76ca-1e56-70ac9dde8a81">This is a useful identity. For the special case of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></stem> samples, it follows from <xref target="eq1"/> that</p>

<formula id="_9ceae334-faaf-4008-2b36-6da77741ed09" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mover accent="true"><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle></mrow></mfrac><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle></mrow></mfrac><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_c066e9ce-abfa-ceda-cfb8-58239e54e258">and similarly</p>

<formula id="_b51179cd-bea4-b917-fc99-1f25472b4394" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mover accent="true"><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle></mrow></mfrac><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>.</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_3bc3701e-2aa1-5aea-7b06-b6aae52ce862">Hence, the relation <xref target="eq5"/> takes the form</p>

<formula id="eq6"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></mfrac><mfenced open="[" close="]"><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><msubsup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>+</mo><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><msubsup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle></mrow></mfrac><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_e528e6ec-e081-462f-b046-ddbc0f7e3688">in agreement with a result given in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/>.</p>

<p id="_1f9ee9b6-e8f5-386b-947d-b33174ece8de">This procedure can be taken a step furthero To see this, let us recall the general formula for the variance <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced></math></stem> of a weighted mean value <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></math></stem>, based on m measured results <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> with statistical weights <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem>. This expression is known to be given by</p>

<formula id="eq7"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mrow><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></munderover><msub><mrow><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>m</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></munderover><msub><mrow><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></mfrac><mo>.</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_24cae887-0082-2dd5-dbb6-628100e1ea68">Since in our case, i.e. for the measurement <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> the sample sizes <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> correspond to the weights <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> we have the relation</p>

<formula id="_05fbf933-8478-3fd6-3bdf-349d8200c1a2" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></munderover><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mover accent="true"><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>m</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><munder><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></munder><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>⋅</mo><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced></math></stem></formula>

<formula id="eq8"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>m</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>⋅</mo><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_13a3efb0-ee14-8770-5bbe-125b16bc4aea">as <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><munder><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></munder><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle></math></stem> and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>/</mo><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle></math></stem>.</p>

<p id="_71198cd1-4f4f-5060-e74d-5ae6eee78b2d">Note, however, that the last equation is not an identity: it is a statistical relation. Thus, it does not always hold numerically. It is true on the average and requires that experimental conditions do not change.</p>

<p id="_4d74340c-1754-07d1-0de9-4a960ddfd66f">If we take advantage of <xref target="eq8"/>, <xref target="eq5"/> can be brought into the form</p>

<formula id="_70980eb2-452b-596c-58af-f3b8931d4b82" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>⋅</mo><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><munder><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></munder><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>⋅</mo><msubsup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>+</mo><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>m</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>⋅</mo><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_37ae6528-76b4-ee4f-075a-1fc19b4a7971">or</p>

<formula id="_bf0db77e-7d6c-d542-a981-5b0e129b1b40" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mfenced open="[" close="]"><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>m</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><munder><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></munder><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>⋅</mo><msubsup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>.</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_c09615c8-e5a8-a5ac-f156-e2c1cae4f62c">Hence, we arrive at the general formula</p>

<formula id="eq9"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mrow><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>⋅</mo><msubsup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>N</mi></mstyle><mo>−</mo><mi>m</mi></mrow></mrow></mfrac><mo>,</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_497df159-cf55-9034-2cba-0a22b18e8396">which allows us to obtain the required variance from those measured in the <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>m</mi></math></stem> samples. This form is quite remarkable in that the experimental mean values <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>¯</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem>, present in <xref target="eq5"/>, have disappeared.</p>

<p id="_20d84fc5-3d18-932a-e525-b8b5da098c42">For samples of equal size (<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi></math></stem>) we are readily led to the expression</p>

<formula id="eq10"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></munderover><msubsup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>,</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_7036d15c-85ea-8702-139c-f591be0da365">for which even a knowledge of the sample size is no longer required.</p>

<p id="_9ffc4bfe-7463-b917-affb-c6b7dba7ccb6">A comparison of <xref target="eq10"/> with <xref target="eq3"/> shows that, at least for equal groups of measurements obtained in stable conditions, pooled estimates of both the expectation value and the variance are obtained by simply forming arithmetical means. The reader, in hindsight, should feel free to find this result either trivial or quite remarkable. It is likely, although not proven, that analogous relations hold for the central moments of higher order.</p>
